gitlab2provb31e6729-036e-5cba-905c-6a679.gitlab2provevent_content: Yes, we are now using it as our default tool on our CI. It's very flexible in the policies one can implement, and also very easy to deploy (e.g. could be used directly via Docker, if you are sharing the socket, or you can build an RPM/DEB for your installation).

gitlab2prove95e6fe0-c0c3-549a-8998-212d6.gitlab2provevent_content: E.g. `MINIMUM_IMAGES_TO_SAVE=1 docker-gc` is very useful to clean up everything but the last built image for every container. Useful in order to still keep the cache warm.

gitlab2prov09a1d686-9005-5d8b-ba33-c6432.gitlab2provevent_content:
All in all, the one-liner that you can add to your `cronjob` is:

```
docker run --rm -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock -e MINIMUM_IMAGES_TO_SAVE=1 -e REMOVE_VOLUMES=1 -v /etc:/etc:ro spotify/docker-gc
```

gitlab2prov5ac2c038-1a00-55ac-ba41-a7230.gitlab2provevent_content:
it does look like this is abandoned and should be unreferenced from the manual (https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-runner/-/merge_requests/2712).

in the meantime, the runner documentation does sugegst another tool for this:

https://docs.gitlab.com/runner/executors/docker.html#clearing-docker-cache

... except it's not doing exactly the same thing as this. first off, it's noisy: it will happily tell you `Clearing docker cache...` *every time it runs*. (I sent https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-runner/-/merge_requests/2711 to try to fix this.) 

Second, it doesn't necessarily clean things the same way as `docker system prune` does.

It would be really great if the gitlab.com team could clarify what the best practices are for this here.. Right now I'm using a mix of those two approaches, with this Puppet manifest:

```puppet
  file { '/usr/local/sbin/tpo-docker-clean-cache':
    content => @(EOF),
    #!/bin/sh

    # silent version of /usr/share/gitlab-runner/clear-docker-cache
    # see https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-runner/-/merge_requests/2711
    docker ps -a -q \
      --filter=status=exited \
      --filter=status=dead \
      --filter=label=com.gitlab.gitlab-runner.type=cache | while read container \
        docker rm --volumes "$container" > /dev/null
    done
    | EOF
  }
  # also prune old containers, alongside their volumes, weekly
  cron { 'docker-clear-cache':
    command => '/usr/local/sbin/tpo-docker-clean-cache',
    weekday => 0,
    hour    => 2,
    minute  => 30,
  }
  # purge docker images older than 3 days old, every day
  cron { 'docker-system-prune':
    command => 'docker system prune --filter until=72h -f',
    hour    => 5,
    minute  => 35,
  }
```

gitlab2prov77729063-1442-5ef5-94ad-80af7.gitlab2provevent_content:
If you want to clean up your docker images and volumes once every 24 hours you can just do this:


```
  system_prune:
    image: docker
    command: docker system prune --all --force
    volumes:
      - "/var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock"
    deploy:
      mode: global
      restart_policy:
        delay: 24h

```

Note this is from docker-compose (so it can be deployed via swarm). But you can easily make the same docker run command.

gitlab2provf36657d9-9562-56fe-937d-5a7d6.gitlab2provissue_description:
Today we encountered the problem that our build were failing during npm installs.

Running the gitlab-runner-docker-cleanup container did not help. 
Maybe because it did not run from the beginning in parallel. 

I found we had endless volumes from old builds in `/var/lib/docker/volumes` of container which didn't exist any longer. 

Running the following command freed the inodes: 
`docker volume rm $(docker volume ls -qf dangling=true)`

Maybe it's something to put in the docs here or for ci in general @ayufan

gitlab2prove7f49abf-a2f4-5888-96ae-6b2b2.gitlab2provissue_description:
The cleanup service should clean up exited / dead containers as well as images and caches. I.e. the equivalent of something like this:

`docker ps -a -q -f status=exited -f status=dead | xargs docker rm -v {}`

I don't know enough about docker to say if the `docker system prune` command (or its equivalent API) mentioned in #10 would take care of this.

Hi,

The gitlab-runner-docker-cleanup is very useful but it doesn't support the volume cleanup. I suggest it as a feature.


At the moment, here are the volume cleanup methods :

* docker 1.12:

`docker volume rm $(docker volume ls -q --filter dangling=true)`

* docker 1.13

`docker system prune # clean every unused data - volumes, images...`

gitlab2prov513c4b64-b1a0-51cb-8ca2-8f8e6.gitlab2provmerge_description:
As stated in #5, it's ironic that a cleaning tool takes so much space itself (947MB). Taking advantage of [docker multi-stage builds](https://blog.docker.com/2017/07/multi-stage-builds/), the tool now only takes 14.3MB.

This change might also fix a lot of #14 since it will be just the binary running on top of the latest alpine.

gitlab2prov6971793f-7889-5ac8-b3bb-5dbdb.gitlab2provissue_description:
The goal of this project is to free some disk space. Now this tool itself comes at a weight of 500MB.

This contradiction feels like sarkasm, but I'm sure the author has the best intentions.

The image contains a python, a perl, go installation, some git repos etc. none of which has any use for cleaning up gitlab runner docker images AFAIK.

There's a single go application running inside the container that - AFAIK is working with the system it is actually running on. It would be nice if the tool was available as a simple packaged go application, without the huge, heavy concrete block surrounding it.

Thanks,
*t

gitlab2provbc1a6bf0-5bf1-5ad8-b7e5-c5208.gitlab2provissue_description:
Just stumbled across this tool and it really seems to solve a common problem.
Was using the default Docker setup on CentOS (device-mapper [1] with loop-lvm) and of course the loop file was quickly full.

I since configured Docker to use a proper direct-lvm thinpool volume and it's working fine so far.

So my question is if it's still possible to somehow use this cleanup tool with a devicemapper thin pool since using `df` on the lvm thinpool volume won't work... at least I don't know how...

[1] https://docs.docker.com/engine/userguide/storagedriver/device-mapper-driver/
